\hypertarget{reading-writing-data}{%
\subsection{Reading / Writing Data}\label{reading-writing-data}}

Of course, if we want work on data which is NOT included in R, then we have to \emph{read} that data into R in order to work with it.
That is, the data are normally somewhere on your computer's hard drive (or SSD), and you must run a command in R which \emph{reads} that data into your R environment.

\hypertarget{olympic-athletes-example}{%
\subsubsection{Olympic Athletes Example}\label{olympic-athletes-example}}

Let's look another example, this time with a data set of Olympic athletes.
This is just a subset of the full dataset, to make it easier for you to work with.
Here's how we'll \emph{read} them into R:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# Read the csv file into a data frame called athletes}
\NormalTok{athletes <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{read.csv}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"data_raw/olympic_athletes.csv"}\NormalTok{)}

\CommentTok{# print a summary of the data frame}
\KeywordTok{summary}\NormalTok{(athletes)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

The above command only works because the data set is in a particular location (the data folder), and is in a particular format (csv).
In the sections that follow, we'll discuss how to address both of these issues.

\hypertarget{locating-your-data-set}{%
\subsubsection{Locating your data set}\label{locating-your-data-set}}

R is capable of reading data from your computer, no matter where it is, as long as you ``point'' R to the correct location.
The location is usually specified with a \emph{file path}, which is a character string that specifies the folder structure that holds your file.
By default, R starts ``looking'' from the current working directory, and the file path used was \texttt{data\_raw/olympic\_athletes.csv}.
This means that R will look inside the current working directory for a folder called \texttt{data\_raw}, and if it exists, R will look inside \texttt{data\_raw} for a file called \texttt{olympic\_athletes.csv}.
In this class, you should be working within an rstudio project, which automatically sets the working directory.
If you created the folders as instructed earlier, then you should already have a \texttt{data\_raw} folder in your project directory.

\begin{progress}
Download the olympic athletes data set from \href{data_raw/olympic_athletes.csv}{this link} and save it in your data\_raw folder.
In your progress check document, simply write: ``Olympic Data Downloaded''
\end{progress}

\hypertarget{reading-csv-files}{%
\subsubsection{Reading CSV files}\label{reading-csv-files}}

A common way of storing data in a computer file is called CSV, which stands for \emph{comma-separated values}.
These files are \emph{plain text}, so you can open them in any text editor like Word, Notepad, or even Google Docs.
Just like a data frame, these files contain data in rows and columns, where on each line, the columns are \emph{separated} from each other with a comma (\texttt{,}), which is technically called a \emph{delimiter}.
Programs like Excel, Google Sheets, and R can read these files and understand their row-column structure.
In R, the function to read CSV files (as you saw above) is \texttt{read.csv}.
In addition, if you call up the help file for read.csv using \texttt{?}, you'll see that there are other similar functions as well, including \texttt{read.table}, and \texttt{read.delim}.

\begin{bonus}
In many object oriented languages, the ``dot'' (\texttt{.}) is a special
symbol used to access an attribute or method of an object. In R,
however, variable names and function names can contain a dot, and the
dot has no special purpose. There are some exceptions, however, that
relate to function overloading, and R formulas, but these are advanced
topics that will not be discussed here.
\end{bonus}

These functions are actually all different variations of the same, generic, function called \texttt{read.table}.
The difference is that \texttt{read.csv}, \texttt{read.delim}, and the others make different assumptions about what delimiters are being used, and how decimal numbers are displayed (e.g.~one-and-a-half may be written as \texttt{1.5}, or \texttt{1,5} depending on where you live).
We will discuss functions and arguments more in the next chapter, but for now, see the following table for when to use each function:

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{l|l|l}
\hline
Function & Delimiter & Decimals\\
\hline
read.table & Must specify with sep=... & .\\
\hline
read.csv & , & .\\
\hline
read.csv2 & ; & ,\\
\hline
read.delim & \textbackslash{}t (tab) & .\\
\hline
read.delim2 & \textbackslash{}t (tab) & ,\\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Any of these functions accepts the argument \texttt{header=FALSE}, which indicates that the first row of the file \emph{does not} contain column names.
Without this argument, R will assume the first row \emph{does} contain column names.
If our Olympic athletes data did not contain headers in the first row, we would use this:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{athletes <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{read.csv}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"data_raw/olympic_athletes.csv"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{header=}\OtherTok{FALSE}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{writing-csv-files}{%
\subsubsection{Writing CSV files}\label{writing-csv-files}}

R also has the capability to \emph{write} a data frame to a CSV file on your computer, that could then be read by Excel, Sheets, etc.
Let's suppose we wanted to save a version of the athletes data with only the \texttt{Sex} and \texttt{Age} columns.
We could use the \texttt{write.csv} function:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# make a new data frame with only the Sex and Age columns}
\NormalTok{athletes2 <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{athletes[,}\KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Sex"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"Age"}\NormalTok{)]}

\CommentTok{# save the new data frame as a CSV in the clean data folder}
\KeywordTok{write.csv}\NormalTok{(athletes2, }\StringTok{"data_clean/olympic_athletes_age_sex.csv"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Notice we created a new data frame by selecting only the desired columns.
We will talk more about different ways to select data when we discuss \emph{indexing}.
Notice also that the write.csv function requires that we give it the name of the data frame being saved (\texttt{athletes2}), then the file path for the csv file that the data will be written to (\texttt{"data\_clean/olympic\_athletes\_age\_sex.csv"}).

\begin{caution}
\texttt{write.csv} is an example of a function which takes
\emph{multiple arguments}, separating them with a comma (\texttt{,}).
Usually, these arguments must be specified in order, but more will be
said about this later.
\end{caution}

\begin{progress}
Create a version of the athletes data frame which contains the athletes'
names and their sports. Save the new data frame as a csv file in your
data\_clean folder with the file name
``olympic\_athletes\_name\_sport.csv''. Include the code in your
progress check assignment.
\end{progress}

\begin{caution}
The \texttt{read} and \texttt{write} terminology may seem odd if you
have not heard those terms before. Your computer's hard drive (or SSD)
will store data which will be remembered even after you turn off your
computer. The process of getting data from, and putting data on your
hard drive (or SSD) is called \emph{reading} and \emph{writing}.
\end{caution}

\hypertarget{summary-statistics}{%
\subsection{Summary Statistics}\label{summary-statistics}}

Reading and writing data is useful, but the power of R is \emph{doing interesting things} with the data!
Let's perform a few operations with the Olympic athletes data to demonstrate some important functions for data analysis.
As we've seen, the \texttt{summary} function automatically performs some summary statistics on each column of a data frame.
Let's see how to produce these and other results manually.

\hypertarget{quantitative-variables}{%
\subsubsection{Quantitative Variables}\label{quantitative-variables}}

To showcase the functions R provides to summarize quantitative variables, we'll look at the \texttt{Age} column of our data frame, which is stored as an integer vector in R.

\begin{reflect}
What other R data types might be used to store quantitative data?
\end{reflect}

However, \texttt{Age} contains \texttt{NA} values, as we know from running the following function:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{sum}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{is.na}\NormalTok{(athletes}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Age))   }\CommentTok{# count how many NA's are in the Age column}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] 183
\end{verbatim}

\begin{reflect}
Pause and think through what's happening in the above code. The \texttt{is.na} function returns a logical array which is true whenever the \texttt{Age} column is \texttt{NA}. So why does the \texttt{sum} function produce the number of \texttt{NA}'s?
\end{reflect}

As a cleaning step, we must first remove the \texttt{NA} values:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{age <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{athletes}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Age         }\CommentTok{# assign the Ages column to a variable}
\NormalTok{age <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{age[}\OperatorTok{!}\KeywordTok{is.na}\NormalTok{(age)]   }\CommentTok{# extract only the elements which are not NA (more on this when we discuss advanced indexing)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{bonus}
This type of ``data cleaning'' is a very common first step when
performing data analysis. You will get more opportunities to clean data
later in the course.
\end{bonus}

Here are some functions R provides to summarize quantitative variables.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{age_min <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{min}\NormalTok{(age)     }\CommentTok{# find the minimum age}
\NormalTok{age_med <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{median}\NormalTok{(age)  }\CommentTok{# find the median age}
\NormalTok{age_max <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{max}\NormalTok{(age)     }\CommentTok{# find the maximum age}
\NormalTok{age_mean <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{mean}\NormalTok{(age)   }\CommentTok{# find the average age}
\NormalTok{age_sd <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{sd}\NormalTok{(age)       }\CommentTok{# find the standard deviation of age}
\NormalTok{age_var <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{var}\NormalTok{(age)     }\CommentTok{# find the variance of age}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Let's put all these results in a named list.
In the following code, read the comments carefully to understand how the code is being organized onto multiple lines.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# Create a list containing all the stats}
\NormalTok{age_stats <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{list}\NormalTok{(  }\CommentTok{# R knows that this command continues until a closed parenthesis}
  \DataTypeTok{min =}\NormalTok{ age_min,   }
  \DataTypeTok{median =}\NormalTok{ age_med, }
  \DataTypeTok{max =}\NormalTok{ age_max,    }
  \DataTypeTok{mean =}\NormalTok{ age_mean,  }
  \DataTypeTok{sd =}\NormalTok{ age_sd,      }
  \DataTypeTok{var =}\NormalTok{ age_var}
\NormalTok{)  }\CommentTok{# this could all go on one line, but it looks more organized this way.}
\NormalTok{age_stats}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

[1] 74

\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}

\KeywordTok{hist}\NormalTok{(age, }\DataTypeTok{breaks=}\DecValTok{50}\NormalTok{)}
\KeywordTok{abline}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{v=}\NormalTok{age_mean, }\DataTypeTok{col=}\StringTok{"blue"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{lty=}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{lwd=}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{)}
\KeywordTok{abline}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{v=}\NormalTok{age_med, }\DataTypeTok{col=}\StringTok{"red"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{lty=}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{lwd=}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}

It looks like the distribution of \texttt{Age} is \emph{right skewed}, consistent with the fact that the mean is greater than the median.

Of course, having more than one quantitative variable allows us to compare them against each other.
Here's how to compute the covariance between two quantitative variables:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{cov}\NormalTok{(athletes}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Age, athletes}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Height, }\DataTypeTok{use=}\StringTok{"complete.obs"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] 6.483675
\end{verbatim}

\begin{caution}
The argument r\texttt{use="complete.obs"} is one way to deal with
\texttt{NA} values in the \texttt{cov} function. This makes R remove any
observations which are NA in either the first or second variable. There
are other ways as well, which you can check using the help function:
\texttt{?cov}.
\end{caution}

You can also compute the correlation between two variables like so:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{cor}\NormalTok{(athletes}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Age, athletes}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Height, }\DataTypeTok{use=}\StringTok{"complete.obs"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] 0.1104457
\end{verbatim}

\hypertarget{saving-an-rdata-file}{%
\subsubsection{Saving an RData file}\label{saving-an-rdata-file}}

Finally, we may want to save these results for use \emph{in R} later.
First, we'll create a new list to put our two stats list \emph{in} (remember, we can have lists inside of other lists!).

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# Create list}
\NormalTok{athlete_stats <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{list}\NormalTok{(}
  \DataTypeTok{age =}\NormalTok{ age_stats,}
  \DataTypeTok{sport =}\NormalTok{ sport_stats}
\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{bonus}
Remember that the \texttt{names} function retrieves the column names for a data frame? It also retrieves the names of a list (after all, a data frame is just a fancy list, right?)!
The following commands may be useful for remembering what the contents of our stats list:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \texttt{names(athlete\_stats)}
\item
  \texttt{names(athlete\_stats\$age)}
\item
  \texttt{names(athlete\_stats\$sport)}
\end{itemize}
\end{bonus}

To save these results, we can use the \texttt{saveRDS} function:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{saveRDS}\NormalTok{(athlete_stats, }\StringTok{"data_clean/athlete_stats.rds"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Later, we can use the following command to load the RDS file back into R:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{rm}\NormalTok{(athlete_stats)  }\CommentTok{# remove athlete stats to prove we are loading it from the hard drive}

\NormalTok{athlete_stats <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{readRDS}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"data_clean/athlete_stats.rds"}\NormalTok{)  }\CommentTok{# load the RDS file and name it athlete_stats}

\NormalTok{athlete_stats}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{age   }\CommentTok{# show that we have loaded the data by printing the age stats}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
$min
[1] 12

$median
[1] 25

$max
[1] 74

$mean
[1] 25.65373

$sd
[1] 6.495693

$var
[1] 42.19402
\end{verbatim}

\begin{caution}
Notice the file ends with \emph{.rds}, indicating that this is a special RDS type which can only be read by R.
This is different from other data formats like CSV, which are plain text and can be read by other programs like Excel or Sheets.
RDS should only be used when you want to save work that you want to resume in R later.
If at all possible, you should prefer using plain text formats rather than RDS.
\end{caution}

\begin{bonus}
RDS stands for \emph{R Data Serialization}. This is R's version of object serialization, just like the io.Serializable interface in Java or the pickle module in Python.
As with other languages, R's serialization can only be used in R.
\end{bonus}

The RDS format works for any R Object, not just lists, so it can be used for vectors, matrices, factors, and even functions.

\hypertarget{data-formatting}{%
\subsection{Data Formatting}\label{data-formatting}}

Before we continue working with data, here are a few comments about data formatting.
Many data sets can be thought of as one or more \emph{observations} of one or more \emph{variables}.
R functions work best when the data are formatted into rows and columns, so that each row is an observation, and each column is a variable.
Unfortunately, sometimes data do not follow this convention, or worse, it may not be clear what the observations or variables are.
Working with data often involves answering multiple questions, and different questions may require thinking of observations and variables differently.
In R, there are ways of changing the structure of data to suit your particular needs, but these are intermediate topics which will not be discussed here.

\begin{bonus}
One concept related to data organization is called ``Tidy Data'', which
you can read more about
\href{https://vita.had.co.nz/papers/tidy-data.pdf}{here}. This focus on
tidyness has led to the development of a set of R packages collectively
called the ``tidyverse'', which has become very popular for R analysis.
The tidyverse will not be covered in this class, but a later module will
provide extensive experience with it.
\end{bonus}

\hypertarget{raw-data-vs.-clean-data.}{%
\subsubsection{``Raw'' data vs.~``Clean'' data.}\label{raw-data-vs.-clean-data.}}

Why is there a ``data\_raw'' folder and a ``data\_clean'' folder, and not just a ``data'' folder?
The idea is that the data\_raw folder contains all of the \emph{original} data sets that you start with, before any cleaning or summarization take place, and any cleaned, modified, or created data sets that result from your data analysis should be stored in the ``data\_clean'' folder (or possibly even a ``results'' folder).
This distinction ensures that the original data sets are preserved in their unedited state, just in case you need to start over from the beginning to answer a different question, and in order for others to easily replicate your work.
This is why the data in the folder should be thought of as \emph{read only}.
Sometimes people even modify the permissions of the raw data files on their computer to prevent anyone from accidentally deleting or overwriting the raw data.
The ``clean'' moniker comes from the fact that often times data sets need some ``cleaning'' such as removing duplicates, \texttt{NA} values, discarding irrelevant data, etc.
There are many other ways of organizing data, but the principle here is to separate the original data sets from any intermediate data sets.

\begin{reflect}
Perhaps you've never thought about how data should be structured.
Consider an experiment which measures the temperatures of five guinea pigs is measured for each of four different days.
Think about organizing each row to be a guinea pig and each column to be a day.
Can you think of an R function to compute the average tempareature on day 1?
How about the average temperature for guinea pig 3?
How do your answers change if the data are arranged with days as the rows and guinea pigs as columns?
Can you think of another way to organize the data?
\end{reflect}

\hypertarget{indexing}{%
\subsection{Indexing}\label{indexing}}

Part of doing interesting things with data is being able to select just the data that you need for a particular circumstance.
You've already seen how to get a particular element from a vector or matrix, or a specific component from a list, using \emph{indices}.
A datum's \emph{index} is its position in the vector or list.
For example, to get the second element of a vector \texttt{A}, we use index 2 in square brackets: \texttt{A{[}2{]}}.
The process of selecting elements using their indices is called \emph{indexing}, and R provides multiple ways of indexing vectors.
Below we'll cover some basic indexing and more advanced indexing for the different data structures in R.

\begin{assessment}
Download the \href{assignment_templates/progress_check_4.rmd}{progress
check 4 template} and follow the instructions. That document should
include all progress reports from Section 5.5 through (and including)
Section 6.1
\end{assessment}

\hypertarget{vectors-1}{%
\subsubsection{Vectors}\label{vectors-1}}

Let's define a vector and access an element in the way you already know:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# create an example vector}
\NormalTok{V <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"A"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"B"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"C"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"D"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"E"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"F"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"G"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"H"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"I"}\NormalTok{)}

\CommentTok{# access the 5th element}
\NormalTok{V[}\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{]}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] "E"
\end{verbatim}

\begin{caution}
Unlike many other languages, R indices start with 1, not 0! so the first
element is accessed as \texttt{A{[}1{]}}, etc.
\end{caution}

Here are some other ways you can index as well.
You can access multiple indices at the same time using a numric vector of indices:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{V[}\KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{)]  }\CommentTok{# access elements 1, 2, and 5}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] "A" "B" "E"
\end{verbatim}

If you need to access several indices in a row, you can use a colon (\texttt{:}):

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{V[}\DecValTok{2}\OperatorTok{:}\DecValTok{7}\NormalTok{]  }\CommentTok{# access elements 2 through 7}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] "B" "C" "D" "E" "F" "G"
\end{verbatim}

You can even combine these two methods:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{V[}\KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{1}\OperatorTok{:}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{6}\NormalTok{)]  }\CommentTok{# access elements 1, 2, 3, and 6}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] "A" "B" "C" "F"
\end{verbatim}

Note that the following are all equivalent ways to access the first three elements of \texttt{V}:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \texttt{V{[}1:3{]}}
\item
  \texttt{V{[}c(1,2,3){]}}
\item
  \texttt{V{[}c(1:3){]}}
\item
  \texttt{V{[}c(1:2,3){]}}
\item
  can you think of another example?
\end{itemize}

But the first way would probably be the most clear for someone else to understand.
All of these methods can work with \emph{assignment} as well:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{V[}\KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{7}\OperatorTok{:}\DecValTok{9}\NormalTok{)] <-}\StringTok{ "X"}  \CommentTok{# change elements 1, 7, 8, and 9 to "X"}
\NormalTok{V}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] "X" "B" "C" "D" "E" "F" "X" "X" "X"
\end{verbatim}

\begin{caution}
Even though these examples use a character vector, this indexing works
on vectors of any type.
\end{caution}

\hypertarget{matrices-1}{%
\subsubsection{Matrices}\label{matrices-1}}

To access an element of a matrix, we have to specify the row and the column.
Let's create a matrix from the \texttt{V} vector and access one of its elements:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{M <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{matrix}\NormalTok{(V, }\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{)  }\CommentTok{# create matrix M with data from vector V}
\NormalTok{M}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
     [,1] [,2] [,3]
[1,] "X"  "D"  "X" 
[2,] "B"  "E"  "X" 
[3,] "C"  "F"  "X" 
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{M[}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{]  }\CommentTok{# access the element in row 1, column 2}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] "D"
\end{verbatim}

Recall that we can access an entire row or column by leaving the \emph{other} index blank:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{M[}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,]  }\CommentTok{# access the entire first row}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] "X" "D" "X"
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{M[,}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{]  }\CommentTok{# access the entire second column}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] "D" "E" "F"
\end{verbatim}

But any of the indexing we just used for vectors can also be used on matrices

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{M[}\DecValTok{1}\OperatorTok{:}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, }\KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{)]  }\CommentTok{# access the elements in rows 1 and 2, columns 2 and 3.}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
     [,1] [,2]
[1,] "D"  "X" 
[2,] "E"  "X" 
\end{verbatim}

Finally, there is one more way of indexing Matrices (for now), that provides only \emph{one} index:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{M[}\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{]  }\CommentTok{# access the "5th" element of the matrix}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] "E"
\end{verbatim}

If you give one index, then R will count down the first row, then the second, then the third, etc., until it reaches the index you specified.
Notice how this agrees with the 5th element of the matrix \texttt{V}, which was used to make our matrix!
And finally, as before, any of these indexing methods can be used to change an element's value:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{M[}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{1}\OperatorTok{:}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{] <-}\StringTok{ "Hats"}
\NormalTok{M}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
     [,1]   [,2]   [,3]  
[1,] "X"    "D"    "X"   
[2,] "Hats" "Hats" "Hats"
[3,] "C"    "F"    "X"   
\end{verbatim}

\hypertarget{lists-1}{%
\subsubsection{Lists}\label{lists-1}}

So far we've discussed three different ways of accessing elements in a list:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{L <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{list}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{A =} \StringTok{"apple"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{b =} \StringTok{"banana"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{c=}\StringTok{"cherry"}\NormalTok{)}

\NormalTok{L[[}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{]]  }\CommentTok{# access using index number}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] "apple"
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{L[[}\StringTok{"b"}\NormalTok{]]  }\CommentTok{# access using component name}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] "banana"
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{L}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{c  }\CommentTok{# access using component name and dollar sign notation}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] "cherry"
\end{verbatim}

And these are basically the only option.
Unfortunately, you \emph{cannot} use a vector of indices in order to access multiple list components at once:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{L[[}\DecValTok{1}\OperatorTok{:}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{]]  }\CommentTok{# this does not work}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{bonus}
What \texttt{L{[}{[}1:3{]}{]}} \emph{actually} does (as the error message might suggest), is access elements within a \emph{nested} list, but that is beyond the scope of this class.
\end{bonus}

\hypertarget{data-frames-1}{%
\subsubsection{Data Frames}\label{data-frames-1}}

Remember that data frames are just lists of vectors, so the same indexing rules of lists and vectors apply.
But remember that matrix indexing rules also apply!
Here are some examples with the Olympic athletes data.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{athletes3 <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{athletes[}\DecValTok{1}\OperatorTok{:}\DecValTok{20}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\OperatorTok{:}\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{]  }\CommentTok{# get the first 20 rows and first 5 columns, and assign it to athletes3}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{athletes3}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Name  }\CommentTok{# get the Name column}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
 [1] "Berta Hrub"                           
 [2] "Joaquim Vital"                        
 [3] "Madelon Baans"                        
 [4] "Achille Canna"                        
 [5] "Antje Buschschulte (-Meeuw)"          
 [6] "Ludwig Gredler"                       
 [7] "Pawe Abratkiewicz"                    
 [8] "Jerzy Zdzisaw Janikowski"             
 [9] "Giuseppe \"Peppino\" Tanti"           
[10] "Carl-Jan Gustaf David Hamilton"       
[11] "Bla Nagy"                             
[12] "Vincent Vittoz"                       
[13] "Joyce May Racek (-Markley, -Budrunas)"
[14] "Seiichiro Kashio"                     
[15] "Surzer"                               
[16] "Dimitrios Kantzias"                   
[17] "Kim Gwang-Suk"                        
[18] "Joshua Noel \"Josh\" Laban"           
[19] "Alejandro Vidal Arellano"             
[20] "Mariusz Latkowski"                    
\end{verbatim}

Remember that each column of a data frame is just a vector, so we can use list indexing to access the \texttt{Name} column, then \emph{immediately} use vector indexing to get only the indices that we want:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{athletes3}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Name[}\DecValTok{1}\OperatorTok{:}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{]  }\CommentTok{# get the first three elements of the Name column}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] "Berta Hrub"    "Joaquim Vital" "Madelon Baans"
\end{verbatim}

\begin{caution}
Notice how With lists, you \emph{cannot} access multiple components
(which is what dataframe columns are) at the same time, but with
matrices you \emph{can} access multiple columns at once. Since data
frames can use matrix formatting, you \emph{can} select multiple columns
at once, as the first example above showed.
\end{caution}

You can also access columns by name like so:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{athletes3[,}\KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Name"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"Sex"}\NormalTok{)]  }\CommentTok{# Access Name and Sex columns}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{bonus}
Think it's weird that data frames can be indexed like matrices? It gets weirder. When vectors have names, they can be indexed like lists! Try for yourself: create a vector \texttt{a\ \textless{}-\ c(1,\ 2,\ 3)} and set the names with \texttt{names(a)\ \textless{}-\ c("angus",\ "brillow",\ "chandelier")} , then see what happens if you type \texttt{a{[}{[}"angus"{]}{]}}! Matrices can also be accessed using names as well.
\end{bonus}

\hypertarget{advanced-indexing}{%
\subsubsection{Advanced Indexing}\label{advanced-indexing}}

There are \emph{even more} ways to select the data you need from your R data structures, let's look some more advanced techniques.

\hypertarget{logical-based-indexing}{%
\paragraph{Logical Based Indexing}\label{logical-based-indexing}}

One \emph{very} useful method that R provides is to access elements of a vector using a different, logical vector of the same length.
As the following example will show, R will give only the elements which are true in the logical vector:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{v <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"alpha"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"bravo"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"charlie"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"delta"}\NormalTok{)  }\CommentTok{# the vector we want to access}
\NormalTok{i <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\OtherTok{FALSE}\NormalTok{, }\OtherTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{, }\OtherTok{FALSE}\NormalTok{, }\OtherTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{)  }\CommentTok{# the logical vector we'll use to index.}

\CommentTok{# index v using i:}
\NormalTok{v[i]}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] "bravo" "delta"
\end{verbatim}

Why is this so useful?
Remember that you can create logical vectors by comparing any type of vector to some value:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{v }\OperatorTok{==}\StringTok{ "delta"}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] FALSE FALSE FALSE  TRUE
\end{verbatim}

This means you can create a logical vector in order to extract only the elements of a vector which match some criterion.
For example, let's create a logical vector based on whether an Olympic athlete's sport was ``Tug-Of-War''.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{plays_tug_of_war <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{athletes}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Sport }\OperatorTok{==}\StringTok{ "Tug-Of-War"}  \CommentTok{# create logical vector}

\KeywordTok{sum}\NormalTok{(plays_tug_of_war)  }\CommentTok{# count how many TRUE's}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] 5
\end{verbatim}

Now let's use that logical vector to get the names of the athletes:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{athletes}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Name[plays_tug_of_war]}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] "Edgar Lindenau Aabye" "Willie Slade"         "William Hirons"      
[4] "Ernest Walter Ebbage" "William Penn"        
\end{verbatim}

\begin{progress}
Using the Olympic athletes data, create a logical vector which is true
when an athlete's sport is wrestling. Then access the age of all
wrestlers, and assign the ages to another vector. Finally, compute the
average age of the wrestlers vector (remember, there may be duplicate
athlete names, so this average won't mean much; the emphasis is on
indexing right now)
\end{progress}

Logical vectors can also be used to subset a data frame based on some condition.
That is, we take entire rows which meet a condition, rather than just a single variable.
For example:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# Subset the athletes data frame to get only Summer athletes.}
\NormalTok{athletes_summer <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{athletes[athletes}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Season }\OperatorTok{==}\StringTok{ "Summer"}\NormalTok{,]}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{caution}
In the last example, we are creating the logical vector and immediately using it to index the rows.
Pause and think through what's happening in this example if it's not quite clear.
Also note the placement of the comma (\texttt{,}), which indicates that we're indexing rows, not columns, of the data frame.
\end{caution}

You can specify multiple conditions using ``and'' (\texttt{\&}) and ``or'' (\texttt{\textbar{}}) like this:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# create logical vector which is true for female gymnasts (female AND gymnast)}
\NormalTok{index <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{(athletes}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Sex }\OperatorTok{==}\StringTok{ "F"}\NormalTok{) }\OperatorTok{&}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{(athletes}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Sport }\OperatorTok{==}\StringTok{ "Gymnastics"}\NormalTok{)}

\CommentTok{# select only female gymnasts}
\NormalTok{fem_gym <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{athletes[index,]}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# create logical vector which is true if sport is basketball OR gymnastics}
\NormalTok{index <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{(athletes}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Sport }\OperatorTok{==}\StringTok{ "Basketball"}\NormalTok{) }\OperatorTok{|}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{(athletes}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Sport }\OperatorTok{==}\StringTok{ "Gymnastics"}\NormalTok{)}

\CommentTok{# select athletes whos sport is basketball OR gymnastics. }
\NormalTok{bb_gy <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{athletes[index,]}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{progress}
Create a data frame called athletes\_winter with only the rows whose \texttt{Season} is ``Winter''
\end{progress}

Another common use for Logical indexing is filling in missing values.
As part of data cleaning, you may decide to change \texttt{NA}'s to some other value. This is easy since we can create a logical vector which is \texttt{TRUE} when a value is \texttt{NA}.
We can do this with the \texttt{is.na} function:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# For athletes with no medal, replace `NA` with "No Medal"}
\NormalTok{athletes}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Medal[}\KeywordTok{is.na}\NormalTok{(athletes}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Medal)] <-}\StringTok{ "No Medal"}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{progress}
Run the above code to replace NA values with ``No Medal'', and save the
file in your data\_clean folder as ``athletes\_clean.csv''
\end{progress}

\begin{caution}
This is not an endorsement of a particular approach to handling missing
values. There are many situation dependent considerations that should be
made in order to decide the best thing to do.
\end{caution}

\hypertarget{negative-indexing}{%
\paragraph{Negative Indexing}\label{negative-indexing}}

Sometimes it's easier to specify which columns or rows should be \emph{excluded} from indexing, rather than those that should be \emph{included}.
To select every column except the first one, you can use a negative index:

\begin{Shaded}

\NormalTok{athletes[,}\OperatorTok{-}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{]  }\CommentTok{# leave out the ID column}

\hypertarget{nested-indexing-13}{%
\paragraph{Nested Indexing: {[}{[}1{]}{]}{[}3{]}}\label{nested-indexing-13}}

In R, it's likely that at some point you will encounter nested data structures, such as vectors within lists (data frames!) and lists within lists.
This might make indexing more confusing at first, but a little practice will help you keep things organized in your mind.
Consider the following example:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# create a vector and a matrix}
\NormalTok{V <-}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{1}\OperatorTok{:}\DecValTok{16}
\NormalTok{M <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{matrix}\NormalTok{(V, }\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{)}

\CommentTok{# create a list which contains them:}
\NormalTok{L <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{list}\NormalTok{(V, M)}

\CommentTok{# create a character vector}
\NormalTok{C <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"I"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"think"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"therefore"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"I"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"am"}\NormalTok{)}

\CommentTok{# create another list which will contain L and C:}
\NormalTok{L2 <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{list}\NormalTok{(L, C)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

With lists like this, it's easy to see code like \texttt{L2{[}{[}1{]}{]}{[}{[}2{]}{]}{[}2,3{]}} and get confused about what is happening.
It's best to break down the statement from left to right

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{L2                 }\CommentTok{# the second list, L2}
\NormalTok{L2[[}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{]]            }\CommentTok{# the first component of L2, which is the first list, L}
\NormalTok{L2[[}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{]][[}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{]]       }\CommentTok{# the second element of L, which is the matrix M}
\NormalTok{L2[[}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{]][[}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{]][}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{]  }\CommentTok{# the second row and third column of M.}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{caution}
We have discussed quite a few ways to index data, but rest assured there
are more ways that we did not discuss! We won't address them now, to
keep things simple!
\end{caution}

\end{feedback}

\hypertarget{visualization}{%
\subsection{Visualization}\label{visualization}}

R is incredibly useful for creating visualizations and graphics which are easy to customize and automate, and entire university courses are dedicated to creating visualizations with R.
Here we can only introduce the basics of creating visualizations in R.

\begin{caution}
In this course, we focus on the visualizations in ``base R'', not the capabilities provided by outside sources.
This means we will not discuss the very popular \texttt{ggplot2} package, which has a very different way of constructing visualizations that could be confusing if included here.
\end{caution}

R can make several different types of plots, and the type of plot will depend on what kind of data you are dealing with.
Below, we'll explore common types of plots for various types of data.

\hypertarget{one-quantitative-variable}{%
\subsubsection{One Quantitative Variable}\label{one-quantitative-variable}}

One of the most popular ways of visualizing quantitative variables is with a histogram, where each bar represents the observations falling within a specific range.
The height of each bar reflects how many observations fall within that range.
In the Olympic athletes data, \texttt{Height} is a quantitative variable, so let's create a histogram using the \texttt{hist} function:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{hist}\NormalTok{(athletes}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Height)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-429-1} \end{center}

This histogram shows that most heights are between roughly 160 and 190 inches, and the distribution looks \emph{unimodal}.
Notice that R has decided how many bins (bars) to use, but this can be changed with the \texttt{breaks} option:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{hist}\NormalTok{(athletes}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Height, }\DataTypeTok{breaks=}\DecValTok{70}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-430-1} \end{center}

R will ``try'' to create the number of bins equal to \texttt{breaks}, but sometimes won't make exactly that number.
Instead of just giving a single number breaks, you could \emph{also} give a vector of numbers, which specify the start and stop points of the bins:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{hist}\NormalTok{(athletes}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Height, }\DataTypeTok{breaks=}\KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{120}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{130}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{140}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{150}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{160}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{170}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{180}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{190}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{200}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{210}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{220}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{230}\NormalTok{))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-431-1} \end{center}

By default, R adds a title and axis labels to the plot, but for presentation purposes, it's probably a good idea to change them.
This can be done with the \texttt{main}, \texttt{xlab}, and \texttt{ylab} options:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{hist}\NormalTok{(athletes}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Height, }\DataTypeTok{breaks=}\DecValTok{60}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{main=}\StringTok{"Olympic Athlete Heights"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{xlab=}\StringTok{"Height (in)"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{ylab=}\StringTok{""}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-432-1} \end{center}

These arguments work with many plot types in R.
In this example, we removed the y label by setting it to be an empty string.

\begin{progress}
Using the clean athletes data, make a histogram of height for athletes
whose sport is Basketball. Hint: It might be easiest to create a new
data frame with only basketball players first. Give it an appropriate
title and axis labels.
\end{progress}

\begin{bonus}
To see more options for the \texttt{hist} function, run \texttt{?hist}.
\end{bonus}

Another way to summarize a quantitative variable is with a boxplot, which shows a box whose boundaries are the first and third quartile. Inside the box, a line denotes the median, and the ``whiskers'' outside the box show which points are outliers (those outside the whiskers).

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{boxplot}\NormalTok{(athletes}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Height)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-435-1} \end{center}

In this case, there are no default title or labels, but we can still add them:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{boxplot}\NormalTok{(athletes}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Height, }\DataTypeTok{main=}\StringTok{"Olympic Athlete Height"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{ylab=}\StringTok{"Height (in)"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-436-1} \end{center}
\begin{caution}
Hint: In RMarkdown, boxplots may look too wide by default. You can control the width of a figure by using the \texttt{fig.height} and \texttt{fig.width} commands in the chunk header like this:

\texttt{\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\textasciigrave{}\{r,\ fig.height=3,\ fit.width=5\}}

These are the values used for the boxplot above.
\end{caution}

The boxplot function also allows you to split up a quantitative variable using another variable, using the tilde (\texttt{\textasciitilde{}}).
Here are some examples:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{boxplot}\NormalTok{(athletes}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Height }\OperatorTok{~}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{athletes}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Sex)  }\CommentTok{# Make a boxplot of height, split by sex}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-438-1} \end{center}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{par}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{mar=}\KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{11}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{) }\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{ }\FloatTok{0.1}\NormalTok{)  }\CommentTok{# command to make the labels fit}
\KeywordTok{boxplot}\NormalTok{(athletes}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Height }\OperatorTok{~}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{athletes}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Sport, }\DataTypeTok{las=}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{xlab=}\StringTok{""}\NormalTok{)  }\CommentTok{# Make a boxplot of height, split by Sport}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-440-1} \end{center}

Here we've added a few more bits to fit all the sport labels in: the \texttt{las} option rotates the labels, and the \texttt{par} function is used to increase the bottom margin below the graph.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{boxplot}\NormalTok{(athletes}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Height }\OperatorTok{~}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{athletes}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Age)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-441-1} \end{center}

\begin{caution}
Different software will use different rules to determine how far out the
``whiskers'' go (and therefore which points are outliers). The default
in R is 1.5 times the interquartile range, but this can be changed. When
you view a boxplot, never assume what rule was used!
\end{caution}

\begin{progress}
Using the clean athletes data, make boxplots of Height for athletes
whose Sport is ``Cycling'', separated by Medal. Give it an appropriate
title and axis labels. Comment on the differences in Height between the
different categories. How many Cyclists have no height reported (that
is, how many have \texttt{NA} for Height) and how many athletes have a
height? How should this affect your interpretation of the boxplots?
\end{progress}

\hypertarget{two-quantitative-variables}{%
\subsubsection{Two Quantitative Variables}\label{two-quantitative-variables}}

The most straightforward way to visualize two quantitative variables is with a scatter plot.
In R, this is created with the \texttt{plot} function.
Let's look at the relationship between height and weight in the Olympic athletes data, but only for a few sports.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# select only some sports}
\NormalTok{gy_bb_wr <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{athletes[athletes}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Sport }\OperatorTok{%in%}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Gymnastics"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"Basketball"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"Wrestling"}\NormalTok{),]}

\KeywordTok{plot}\NormalTok{(gy_bb_wr}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Height, gy_bb_wr}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Weight)  }\CommentTok{# plot height vs weight}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-444-1} \end{center}
\begin{bonus}
Above we saw another nice way to index: the \texttt{\%in\%} command.
This returns a logical vector which is true for elements that are found
in the search list.
\end{bonus}

There are a lot of points, so it may be useful to decrease the size of the circles using the \texttt{cex} option, which has a default value of 1:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{plot}\NormalTok{(gy_bb_wr}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Height, gy_bb_wr}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Weight, }\DataTypeTok{cex=}\FloatTok{0.4}\NormalTok{)  }\CommentTok{# Make circles smaller}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-446-1} \end{center}

Another option would be to change the type of marker, which can be selected using the \texttt{pch} option.
We'll choose a smaller, solid circle, which is marker number 20:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{plot}\NormalTok{(gy_bb_wr}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Height, gy_bb_wr}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Weight, }\DataTypeTok{pch=}\DecValTok{20}\NormalTok{)  }\CommentTok{# try filled circles}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-447-1} \end{center}

We can also set the color using the \texttt{col} argument.
There are multiple ways to specify a color, but we'll use the \texttt{rgb} function, which allows us to specify how much red, green, and blue the color has.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{color <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{rgb}\NormalTok{(}\FloatTok{0.5}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{)}
\KeywordTok{plot}\NormalTok{(gy_bb_wr}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Height, gy_bb_wr}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Weight, }\DataTypeTok{pch=}\DecValTok{20}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{col=}\NormalTok{color)  }\CommentTok{# change color}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-448-1} \end{center}

Lastly, we can also make the points less visible, so it's easier to see when they are overlapping one another.
This is done when defining the color, by giving a fourth value called the \emph{alpha}, which represents how visible a point is.
An alpha value of 0 is invisible, and a value of 1 is fully visible.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{color <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{rgb}\NormalTok{(}\FloatTok{0.5}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, }\FloatTok{0.1}\NormalTok{)  }\CommentTok{# set the alpha level low, so points are transparent}
\KeywordTok{plot}\NormalTok{(gy_bb_wr}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Height, gy_bb_wr}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Weight, }\DataTypeTok{pch=}\DecValTok{20}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{col=}\NormalTok{color)  }\CommentTok{# make points partially transparent}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-449-1} \end{center}

We can also color by sport, by converting the Sport column to a factor, then giving that as the color argument:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{colors <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{as.factor}\NormalTok{(gy_bb_wr}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Sport)}
\KeywordTok{plot}\NormalTok{(gy_bb_wr}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Height, gy_bb_wr}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Weight, }\DataTypeTok{pch=}\DecValTok{20}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{col=}\NormalTok{colors)  }\CommentTok{# color by sport}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-450-1} \end{center}
\begin{caution}
We convert Sport to a factor because the \texttt{col} option in plot is
expecting either a single color (as in the first example) or a vector of
numbers indicating which color should be used for each point (remember,
factors are represented as numbers). The numbers tell R which color in
its palette it should use (for the default palette, 1=black, 2=reddish,
3=greenish, etc.), so factor level 1 (Basketball) is colored black,
level 2 (Gymnastics) is colored reddish, and level 3 (Wrestling) is
colored greenish.
\end{caution}

The default colors in R are sometimes not very appealing, so we can define our own color palette:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{palette}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{rgb}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{,}\FloatTok{0.1}\NormalTok{), }\KeywordTok{rgb}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{,}\FloatTok{0.1}\NormalTok{), }\KeywordTok{rgb}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\FloatTok{0.1}\NormalTok{)))   }\CommentTok{# create color palette}
\KeywordTok{plot}\NormalTok{(gy_bb_wr}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Height, gy_bb_wr}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Weight, }\DataTypeTok{pch=}\DecValTok{20}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{col=}\NormalTok{colors)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-452-1} \end{center}

In some cases, it might be appropriate to use lines instead of points.
This can be done by setting the \texttt{type} option to ``l'':

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{x <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{1}\OperatorTok{:}\DecValTok{10}\NormalTok{)}\OperatorTok{/}\DecValTok{10} \OperatorTok{*}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{2}\OperatorTok{*}\NormalTok{pi}
\NormalTok{y <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{sin}\NormalTok{(x)}
\KeywordTok{plot}\NormalTok{(x, y, }\DataTypeTok{type=}\StringTok{"l"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-453-1} \end{center}

You can use points and lines at the same time using ``b'':

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{plot}\NormalTok{(x, y, }\DataTypeTok{type=}\StringTok{"b"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-454-1} \end{center}

Another option for plotting two quantitative variables, especially when there are many overlapping points, is the smooth scatter:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{smoothScatter}\NormalTok{(gy_bb_wr}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Height, gy_bb_wr}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Weight)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-455-1} \end{center}

\hypertarget{one-categorical-variables}{%
\subsubsection{One Categorical Variables}\label{one-categorical-variables}}

One useful way to visualize categorical variables is bar plots.
Before creating a barplot, we need to create a summary table of the variable of interest:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{sport_tab <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{table}\NormalTok{(gy_bb_wr}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Sport)}
\KeywordTok{barplot}\NormalTok{(sport_tab, }\DataTypeTok{col=}\KeywordTok{rgb}\NormalTok{(}\FloatTok{0.2}\NormalTok{, }\FloatTok{0.2}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-457-1} \end{center}

\begin{progress}
Create a barplot for the Season variable, with an appropriate title and
axis labels. Which Season has more rows in the data frame??
\end{progress}

\hypertarget{two-categorical-variables}{%
\subsubsection{Two Categorical Variables}\label{two-categorical-variables}}

With two categorical variables, you can create a mosaicplot, where the size of each region is relative to the number of observations in that group.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{mosaicplot}\NormalTok{(gy_bb_wr}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Sport }\OperatorTok{~}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{gy_bb_wr}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Sex, }\DataTypeTok{col=}\KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"blue"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"orange"}\NormalTok{), }\DataTypeTok{main=}\StringTok{"Athlete Sex by Sport"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{xlab=}\StringTok{"Sport"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{ylab=}\StringTok{"Sex"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-459-1} \end{center}

\hypertarget{multiple-plots}{%
\subsubsection{Multiple plots}\label{multiple-plots}}

One nice feature of R's plotting capability is that you can plot multiple things at the same time.
One way to do this is to create a plot and then add another plot \emph{on top} of it, using either the \texttt{points} or \texttt{lines} function.
\texttt{points} will add a scatter plot using lines, and \texttt{lines} will add a scatter plot using a line.
Normally, a plotting function like \texttt{plot} or \texttt{hist} will create a new plot \emph{figure}, erasing what may have been plotted before.
But with the \texttt{points} and \texttt{lines} functions, R just adds to the existing figure.
Here's an example of each:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# create some data to plot}
\NormalTok{x <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{1}\OperatorTok{:}\DecValTok{100}\NormalTok{)}\OperatorTok{/}\DecValTok{100}
\NormalTok{y1 <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{x}
\NormalTok{y2 <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{sin}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{3}\OperatorTok{/}\NormalTok{x)}\OperatorTok{*}\NormalTok{x}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{plot}\NormalTok{(x, y2,)  }\CommentTok{# plot x against y2}
\KeywordTok{points}\NormalTok{(x, y1, }\DataTypeTok{col=}\StringTok{"blue"}\NormalTok{)  }\CommentTok{# add points of x against y1 (on same figure)}
\KeywordTok{lines}\NormalTok{(x, }\OperatorTok{-}\NormalTok{y1, }\DataTypeTok{col=}\StringTok{"red"}\NormalTok{)  }\CommentTok{# add lines of x against -y1 (on same figure)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-462-1} \end{center}

\hypertarget{other-types-of-plots}{%
\subsubsection{Other types of plots}\label{other-types-of-plots}}

The following plots that are less common, but may be useful for you, and this is an opportunity to show some other capabilities of R!

\hypertarget{scatterplot-matrix}{%
\paragraph{Scatterplot Matrix}\label{scatterplot-matrix}}

Given several quantitative variables, there are many different possible scatterplots you could make.
The \texttt{pairs} function takes in a matrix or data frame and creates a matrix of all possible scatter plots.
Here's an example using the \texttt{iris} data set which is included in R:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{pairs}\NormalTok{(iris, }\DataTypeTok{pch=}\DecValTok{20}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-463-1} \end{center}

To know the x axis for one of these plots, look up/down to the diagonal, which will tell you the variable on the x axis.
To know the y axis for one of these plots, look left/right to the diagonal, which will tell you the variable on the y axis.

\hypertarget{surfaces}{%
\paragraph{Surfaces}\label{surfaces}}

If you need to plot a surface, there are a few options for visualization.
The first is \texttt{contour}, which shows level curves of the surface in a 2d plane:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# Make a surface using the rep function}
\NormalTok{n <-}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{100}
\NormalTok{x <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{rep}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{1}\OperatorTok{:}\NormalTok{n, n)}\OperatorTok{/}\NormalTok{n}\OperatorTok{*}\DecValTok{2}\OperatorTok{*}\NormalTok{pi}
\NormalTok{y <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{rep}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{1}\OperatorTok{:}\NormalTok{n, }\DataTypeTok{each=}\NormalTok{n)}\OperatorTok{/}\NormalTok{n}\OperatorTok{*}\DecValTok{2}\OperatorTok{*}\NormalTok{pi}
\NormalTok{z <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{matrix}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{sin}\NormalTok{(x) }\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{cos}\NormalTok{(y), n, n)}

\KeywordTok{contour}\NormalTok{(z, }\DataTypeTok{nlevels=}\DecValTok{20}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-464-1} \end{center}

The second option is \texttt{parsp}, which gives a 3d perspective of the surface:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{persp}\NormalTok{(z, }\DataTypeTok{theta=}\DecValTok{45}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{phi=}\DecValTok{30}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{shade=}\FloatTok{0.5}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-465-1} \end{center}

\hypertarget{saving-images}{%
\subsubsection{Saving Images}\label{saving-images}}

Creating visualizations in R wouldn't be very useful if there were no way to save them onto your hard drive (or ssd).
Thankfully, R provides various ways of doing this, depending on where the plot ``lives''.
We'll talk through each of these below.

\hypertarget{rcode}{%
\paragraph{RCode}\label{rcode}}

The most universal way to save plots is to use R code itself! This will work anywhere that R code can be run, whether that's the RStudio console, an R script, or an RMarkdown document.
All you have to do is type a few simple commands.
The idea is, that normally R ``sends'' a plot to the plotting window (in the lower right of RStudio), or to the output of a code chunk (if you're using RMarkdown), but to save the file, you just have to change where R is sending the plot.
For example, if you add put the \texttt{png} function before a plotting command, then instead of sending the plot to wherever it normally does, R will send the plot into the png file you specify.
Here's an example:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{png}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"output/test_plot.png"}\NormalTok{)  }\CommentTok{# start "sending" plots to the png file called "test_plot.png"}
\KeywordTok{plot}\NormalTok{(y1, y2)          }\CommentTok{# this plot will go to "test_plot.png"}
\KeywordTok{dev.off}\NormalTok{()             }\CommentTok{# Stop sending plots to "test_plot.png"}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
pdf 
  2 
\end{verbatim}

After you're done sending plots to a file, use the command \texttt{dev.off()} to reset where R is sending the plots

\begin{bonus}
R graphics works with objects called ``graphics devices''.
The \texttt{png} function creates a new graphics device which is a file on your computer.
The \texttt{dev.off()} shuts down the current graphics device, so no more plots are sent to the file.
You can check out other \texttt{dev.} functions by running `?dev.off().
\end{bonus}

There are other commands like \texttt{png} as well, including \texttt{bmp} for bitmap images, and \texttt{jpeg} for jpeg images.
When you're sending a plot to a file, it will \emph{not} display in the plot window.

\hypertarget{rstudio-plot-window}{%
\paragraph{RStudio Plot Window}\label{rstudio-plot-window}}

If you run code to generate a plot from the console or an R script, then the plot will show up in the RStudio plot window.
To save a figure displayed in the plot window, use the ``Explort'' button in the plot window menu.

\hypertarget{rmarkdown}{%
\paragraph{RMarkdown}\label{rmarkdown}}

If you're plotting inside of an RMarkdown document, then plots will be shown inside your document.
One way to get them ``out of RStudio'' is simply to knit the document.
But if you want the plot by itself, then right click on the plot and select ``Save image as''.

Choose a plot that you previously created, and write code to save the
plot to a png file in the ``output'' directory of your RStudio project.
Choose an appropriate filename for the file.
\end{progress}

\hypertarget{plotting-wrap-up}{%
\subsubsection{Plotting Wrap Up}\label{plotting-wrap-up}}

These examples of plotting are only scratching the surface.
There are many more things possible with base R graphics, not to mention the numerous other capabilities provided by community developed Packages.
Before ending this section, we'll leave you with an example from the \texttt{ggplot2} package, just to give you a taste of what's possible.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{library}\NormalTok{(ggplot2)}

\KeywordTok{ggplot}\NormalTok{(gy_bb_wr, }\KeywordTok{aes}\NormalTok{(Height, Weight, }\DataTypeTok{color=}\NormalTok{Sex)) }\OperatorTok{+}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{geom_point}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{alpha=}\FloatTok{0.2}\NormalTok{) }\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{theme_bw}\NormalTok{() }\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{labs}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{title=}\StringTok{"Athlete Height vs. Weight"}\NormalTok{) }\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{facet_grid}\NormalTok{(Sex}\OperatorTok{~}\NormalTok{Sport)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
Warning: Removed 199 rows containing missing values (geom_point).
\end{verbatim}

\hypertarget{vignettes}{%
\subsection{Vignettes}\label{vignettes}}

In this section, you'll gain more experience working with data by following along with some more data analysis examples.

\hypertarget{flood-analysis-example}{%
\subsubsection{Flood analysis example}\label{flood-analysis-example}}

In this example we will learn how to analyze flood data to better understand
the history of flooding in the last ten years in the Cache La Poudre river
which runs through Fort Collins. This vignette will help you learn three key ideas:

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi})}
\item
  Data can be read into R directly from online data services using \texttt{packages}
  which you will learn about more later in this book.
\item
  We can use this `live' data to understand both past and present river conditions
  in the river.
\item
  We can use R to look at changes over time in river flow and water height.
\end{enumerate}

\hypertarget{map}{%
\paragraph{Map}\label{map}}

The river monitoring location for the Cache La Poudre River is right at Lincoln
Bridge near Odell Brewing.

\hypertarget{installing-and-using-packages}{%
\paragraph{Installing and using packages}\label{installing-and-using-packages}}

In order to download river flow and height data we will first need to load a
package called \texttt{dataRetrieval} this is a package run by the United States
Geological Survey (USGS) and it provides access to data from over 8000
river monitoring
stations in the United States and millions of water quantity and quality
records. You can learn more about the data from the USGS \href{https://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis}{here}. To use packages we first have
to install them using the command \texttt{install.packages} and then load them
using the command \texttt{library}.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{## Install the package if it's not already installed by uncommenting the line }
\CommentTok{#below}

\CommentTok{#install.packages('dataRetrieval')}

\CommentTok{#load the package}
\KeywordTok{library}\NormalTok{(dataRetrieval)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{downloading-the-data}{%
\paragraph{Downloading the data}\label{downloading-the-data}}

Once we have loaded the package we can use
the special functions that it brings to the table. In this case \texttt{dataRetrival}
provides a function called \texttt{readNWISdv} which can download daily data
(or daily values, hence readNWIS\emph{dv}) for specific
monitoring locations. But how do we use this function?
Try \texttt{?readNWISdv} to get more details.
So the \texttt{readNWISdv} command requires a few key arguments. First
\texttt{siteNumbers}, these are simply the site identifiers that the USGS uses
to track different monitoring stations and in our case that number for the
Cache La Poudre is \texttt{06752260}, which you can find \href{https://waterdata.usgs.gov/co/nwis/uv?site_no=06752260}{here}.
The second argument is the \texttt{parameterCd} which
is a cryptic code that indicates what kind of data you want to download. In
this case we want to download river flow data. River
flow tells us how much water is moving past a given point over and is correlated
with the height of the river water. This code is \texttt{00060} for discharge which means
river flow.
Lastly we need to tell the \texttt{readNWISdv} command the time period for which we want
data which is \texttt{startDate} which we will set to 2010,
and \texttt{endDate} which we will set to the current day using the command
\texttt{Sys.Date()}. These arguments should be in the
YYYY-MM-DD format. With all this knowledge of how the command works, we can
finally download some data, directly into R!

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{poudre <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{readNWISdv}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{siteNumbers =} \StringTok{'06752260'}\NormalTok{,}
                     \DataTypeTok{parameterCd =} \KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{'00060'}\NormalTok{),}
                     \DataTypeTok{startDate =} \StringTok{'2010-10-01'}\NormalTok{,}
                     \DataTypeTok{endDate =} \KeywordTok{Sys.Date}\NormalTok{())}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{explore-the-data-structure}{%
\paragraph{Explore the data structure}\label{explore-the-data-structure}}

Now that we have our dataframe called \texttt{poudre}, we can explore the properties
of this data frame using commands we have already learn. First let's
see what the structure of the data is using the \texttt{head} command, which
will print the first 6 rows of data.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{head}\NormalTok{(poudre)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
  agency_cd  site_no       Date X_00060_00003 X_00060_00003_cd
1      USGS 06752260 2010-10-01          20.4                A
2      USGS 06752260 2010-10-02          16.8                A
3      USGS 06752260 2010-10-03          22.6                A
4      USGS 06752260 2010-10-04          99.2                A
5      USGS 06752260 2010-10-05         120.0                A
6      USGS 06752260 2010-10-06         113.0                A
\end{verbatim}

It looks like we have a dataframe that is 5 columns wide with columns \texttt{agency\_cd} which is just the USGS, \texttt{site\_no} which is just the site id we already told it. Since
we only asked for data for one site, we don't really need this column. A \texttt{Date}
column which tells us\ldots{} the date! There are two more columns that are kind of weird which
are labeled \texttt{X\_00060\_00003} which is the column that actually has values of
river flow in Cubic Feet Per Second (cfs), or the amount of water that is flowing
by a location per second in Cubic Feet volume units (1 cubic foot \textasciitilde{} 7.5 gallons).
Finally \texttt{X\_00060\_00003\_cd} tells us something about the quality of the data. For now
we will ignore this final column, but if you were doing an analysis of this data
for a project, you would want to investigate what codes are acceptable for
high quality analyses. To make working with this data a little easier let's
rename and remove some of our columns in a new, simpler data.frame.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{#Remove the first two columns}
\NormalTok{pq <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{poudre[,}\OperatorTok{-}\KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{)]}

\CommentTok{#Rename the remaining columns}
\KeywordTok{names}\NormalTok{(pq) <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{'Date'}\NormalTok{,}\StringTok{'q_cfs'}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{explore-the-data.}{%
\paragraph{Explore the data.}\label{explore-the-data.}}

Now that we have cleaned up our data.frame a little, let's explore the data.
First we can use a summary command to just quickly look at the variables we have.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{summary}\NormalTok{(pq)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
      Date                q_cfs        
 Min.   :2010-10-01   Min.   :   2.60  
 1st Qu.:2013-04-28   1st Qu.:  28.18  
 Median :2015-11-25   Median :  74.10  
 Mean   :2015-11-25   Mean   : 240.75  
 3rd Qu.:2018-06-23   3rd Qu.: 155.00  
 Max.   :2021-01-19   Max.   :7150.00  
\end{verbatim}

It looks like we have data from 2010 to 2021-01-20 and a range in river
flow (q\_cfs) from 2.6 cfs all the way up to 7150 cfs. If you're a hydrologist,
hopefully these flow numbers look right, but another way to check to make sure
is to simply plot the data as we do below.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{plot}\NormalTok{(pq}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{q_cfs }\OperatorTok{~}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{pq}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{Date, }\DataTypeTok{type =} \StringTok{'l'}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{ylab =} \StringTok{'River Flow (cfs)'}\NormalTok{, }
     \DataTypeTok{xlab =} \StringTok{'Date'}\NormalTok{,}\DataTypeTok{col =} \StringTok{'blue3'}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-476-1} \end{center}

\begin{reflect}
The above plot is called a ``hydrograph'' or a plot of how river flow
has changed over time. In the Cache La Poudre, what might explain the
peaks and valleys of the data? What controls river flow in Colorado
rivers.
\end{reflect}

\hypertarget{analyze-the-data}{%
\paragraph{Analyze the data}\label{analyze-the-data}}

Now that we plotted the data we can see some interesting patterns that we
might want to explore. For example how has the average flow changed in the last
ten years. To analyze this we need to use the concept of a \texttt{Water\ Year}. Simply
put, a water year is a way to analyze yearly variation in flow, which doesn't
map well to a calendar year. Water years in the USA are typically from October 1
to September 30th. Luckily for us, the \texttt{dataRetrieval} package has a function
that calculates water year for us. It's simply called \texttt{addWaterYear}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{pq_wy <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{addWaterYear}\NormalTok{(pq)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

To look at variation per year we can use the function called \texttt{tapply} which can take the mean, max or any summary
function of groups of data (more on this in the next chapter, but you can type \texttt{?tapply} for more info).
In this case we want to look at the mean river flow for each water year.
Now to use tapply we use the following code

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{annual <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{tapply}\NormalTok{(pq_wy}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{q_cfs,pq_wy}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{waterYear, mean)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Now let's plot the data, where the values (y) are the annual average flow and the years (x) are the names of the annual vector from the \texttt{tapply} function.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{plot}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{names}\NormalTok{(annual),(annual))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-480-1} \end{center}
\begin{reflect}
Has annual mean river declined over the past ten years? What about the
last 6?
\end{reflect}
