\hypertarget{working-with-popular-packages}{%
\subsection{Working With Popular Packages}\label{working-with-popular-packages}}

\hypertarget{what-is-a-package}{%
\subsubsection{What is a package?}\label{what-is-a-package}}

Up to this point in this book/course, we have really focused on using \texttt{base} R.
By \texttt{base}, we simply mean the functions, data sets, and arguments that come
pre-packaged with R. While this book has (hopefully) shown you just how much
these basic functions can do, R can do so much more by relying on \texttt{packages.}

\texttt{Packages} are an integral part of R programming, and you have been using them
throughout this book and class. A \texttt{package} is a contained set of arguments,
operations, data, and/or other tools that don't come with R. In general
these are built by the vast community of R users and they cover tools from making
beautiful maps in R to doing financial time-series analyses to downloading
and analyzing hydrology data (see Vignettes). In fact, you have been using
\texttt{packages} this whole time. For example, In order to \texttt{knit} a document using RMarkdown, you have to have the \texttt{RMarkdown} package installed.

On many (most?) projects, the most efficient way to complete whatever task you
are doing is to spend at least some time checking out if there is a \texttt{package}
that makes it easier for you to do things like:

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\tightlist
\item
  Download data from the internet
\item
  Perform statistical analyses
\item
  Plot data
\item
  Make maps
\item
  Add interactivity to your R code (like zoomable maps or plots)
\item
  And so much more!
\end{enumerate}

\hypertarget{how-do-i-use-packages}{%
\subsubsection{How do I use packages?}\label{how-do-i-use-packages}}

There are always at least two steps to using any package.

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\tightlist
\item
  Install the package using \texttt{install.packages()}. You only have to do this once.
\item
  Load the package using \texttt{library()}. You have to do this every time you want to use the capabilities of that package, but only once per Script or once per RMarkdown document.
\end{enumerate}

Here is an example with an extremely common plotting package \texttt{ggplot2} you will
work on in the next module (and have probably already seen on the internet)

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{install.packages}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{'ggplot2'}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Now that we've installed the package we can load it into R, using \texttt{library()}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{library}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{'ggplot2'}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Now that we have installed the package we will need to learn how to use it.
Where can we go to for help?

\hypertarget{finding-and-using-package-help.}{%
\subsubsection{Finding and using package help.}\label{finding-and-using-package-help.}}

All R packages installed with \texttt{install.packages} will come from the
\emph{Comprehensive R Archive Network} (``CRAN''). In order for you to work with them
they have to have gone through a minimum overview, which ensures that they
will at least have a minimum help page. So for any package you want to
read more about you can simply search for: \texttt{CRAN\ \textless{}package\ name\textgreater{}}. For \texttt{ggplot2}
this will lead you to \href{https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/ggplot2/index.html}{this website}. This site
outlines many of the resources for using \texttt{ggplot2}, but they can be hard to find.
The two most important places to look for help are the Reference manual and the
URL.

The \href{https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/ggplot2/ggplot2.pdf}{reference manual} will outline every function that the package can perform and how to use the functions.
\texttt{ggplot2} is a big package so it has tons of functions, which is why you might not
want to only use the PDF, which can be hard to navigate. Luckily they made a website
that is more clear and has far more examples \href{https://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/}{here}.

\hypertarget{making-beautiful-plots-with-ggplot2}{%
\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Making Beautiful Plots with \emph{ggplot2}}{Making Beautiful Plots with ggplot2}}\label{making-beautiful-plots-with-ggplot2}}

Our package is now loaded, we have a manual for reference so let's use it!

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# Making up data for plotting}
\NormalTok{dat <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{data.frame}\NormalTok{( }\DataTypeTok{response =} \KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{10}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{30}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{100}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{300}\NormalTok{),}
                   \DataTypeTok{driver =} \KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{6}\NormalTok{))}

\CommentTok{# Make a scatter plot with x and y }
\KeywordTok{ggplot}\NormalTok{(dat, }\KeywordTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{x =}\NormalTok{ driver, }\DataTypeTok{y =}\NormalTok{ response)) }\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{geom_point}\NormalTok{()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-582-1} \end{center}

In the above command \texttt{ggplot2} uses the data frame \texttt{dat} and the aesthetics (\texttt{aes})
argument to map which columns go where. In this case we want the driver variable
to be on the x-axis and the response variable to be on the y-axis. Finally
we want to use points to display this relationship between x and y (\texttt{geom\_point}).

\begin{caution}
Note: \texttt{ggplot2} connects a series of arguments using \texttt{+}
operator. This is unique to \texttt{ggplot}, but it's a helpful way to
make complex plots by combining simpler pieces. This can be difficult to
get used to, but can be very powerful when you get the hang of it.
\end{caution}

Let's add some lines to connect the points using the \texttt{geom\_line()} command.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{ggplot}\NormalTok{(dat, }\KeywordTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{x =}\NormalTok{ driver, }\DataTypeTok{y =}\NormalTok{ response)) }\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{geom_point}\NormalTok{() }\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{geom_line}\NormalTok{()  }\CommentTok{# add lines to connect the points}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-584-1} \end{center}
\begin{bonus}
The \texttt{geom} prefix on the \texttt{geom\_point} and
\texttt{geom\_line} functions stands for \emph{geometry}.
\texttt{ggplot2} comes with many different types of geometries (see
\href{https://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/reference/}{here} ), and some folks
have created their \emph{own} packages to add \emph{even more} options!
\end{bonus}

We can also change the way the lines and points look with arguments in the \texttt{geom\_point} and \texttt{geom\_line} functions:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{ggplot}\NormalTok{(dat, }\KeywordTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{x =}\NormalTok{ driver, }\DataTypeTok{y =}\NormalTok{ response)) }\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{geom_point}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{color=}\StringTok{"blue"}\NormalTok{) }\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{                   }\CommentTok{# make the points blue}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{geom_line}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{linetype=}\StringTok{"dashed"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{color=}\StringTok{"blue"}\NormalTok{)   }\CommentTok{# make the lines dashed and blue}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-586-1} \end{center}

We can add a title and axis labels using the \texttt{labs} function:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{ggplot}\NormalTok{(dat, }\KeywordTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{x =}\NormalTok{ driver, }\DataTypeTok{y =}\NormalTok{ response)) }\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{geom_point}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{color=}\StringTok{"blue"}\NormalTok{) }\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{geom_line}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{linetype=}\StringTok{"dashed"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{color=}\StringTok{"blue"}\NormalTok{) }\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{labs}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{title=}\StringTok{"Driver vs. Response"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{x=}\StringTok{"Driver"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{y=}\StringTok{"Response"}\NormalTok{)   }\CommentTok{# add labels to the plot}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-587-1} \end{center}

Finally, we can use one of the included \texttt{ggplot2} themes to change how the plot looks, using the \texttt{theme\_set} function:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{theme_set}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{theme_minimal}\NormalTok{())   }\CommentTok{# change the theme}

\KeywordTok{ggplot}\NormalTok{(dat, }\KeywordTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{x =}\NormalTok{ driver, }\DataTypeTok{y =}\NormalTok{ response)) }\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{geom_point}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{color=}\StringTok{"blue"}\NormalTok{) }\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{geom_line}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{linetype=}\StringTok{"dashed"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{color=}\StringTok{"blue"}\NormalTok{) }\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{labs}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{title=}\StringTok{"Driver vs. Response"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{x=}\StringTok{"Driver"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{y=}\StringTok{"Response"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-588-1} \end{center}

Here's another example using the \texttt{mtcars} data frame, where we color the points based on their fuel economy (\emph{mpg}) and annotate a few cars.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{mtcars}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{car <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{row.names}\NormalTok{(mtcars)  }\CommentTok{# turn row names into a column so we can label with them}

\KeywordTok{ggplot}\NormalTok{(mtcars, }\KeywordTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{x=}\NormalTok{hp, }\DataTypeTok{y=}\NormalTok{disp, }\DataTypeTok{color=}\NormalTok{mpg, }\DataTypeTok{label=}\NormalTok{car)) }\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{geom_point}\NormalTok{() }\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{geom_text}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{color=}\StringTok{"black"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{hjust=}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{nudge_x=}\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{alpha=}\FloatTok{0.8}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{size=}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{) }\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{   }\CommentTok{# annotate each car}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{scale_color_viridis_c}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{option=}\StringTok{"D"}\NormalTok{) }\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{                                 }\CommentTok{# change color scale to use}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{labs}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{title=}\StringTok{"Motor Trend Car Comparison"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{x=}\StringTok{"Horsepower"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{y=}\StringTok{"Displacement"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{color=}\StringTok{"MPG"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{Module1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-589-1} \end{center}

This is only scratching the surface of what \texttt{ggplot2} can do, but hopefully this introduction is enough to hint at the possibilities.
You can find many more examples at \href{https://www.r-graph-gallery.com/}{The R Graph Gallery}.

\begin{progress}
(No need to turn this in) Create a plot of \texttt{wt} vs.~\texttt{mpg}
using the \texttt{mtcars} data frame using \texttt{ggplot2}. Make the
points green.
\end{progress}

\hypertarget{organizing-your-data-with-dplyr}{%
\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Organizing Your Data With \emph{dplyr}}{Organizing Your Data With dplyr}}\label{organizing-your-data-with-dplyr}}

As we saw, \texttt{ggplot2} is a package intended to make nice looking visualizations in R easy.
This is interesting, because R \emph{already has} the capability to make plots, it's just that \texttt{ggplot2} is \emph{another way} of making plots which many people think is more powerful.
The same can be said about the next package we'll discuss, \texttt{dplyr} (rhymes with ``deep liar''), which is \emph{another way} of manipulating data in R.
We've spent a considerable amount of time on \emph{indexing}, and you may have found the process somewhat confusing.
Well, \texttt{dplyr} is another way of indexing data frames that many people find to be more intuitive.
As always, you have to install \texttt{dplyr} if you haven't already.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{install.packages}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"dplyr"}\NormalTok{)  }\CommentTok{# install using quotes!}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Then whenever you'd like to use the package, you have to load it:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{library}\NormalTok{(dplyr)  }\CommentTok{# load without using quotes!}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Let's look at some exmples of \texttt{base} R indexing and compare that to how \texttt{dplyr} accomplishes the same task.

In \texttt{base} R, to select columns matching a certain condition, you create a logical vector and use it to index rows of the data frame

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{index <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{(mtcars}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{cyl }\OperatorTok{==}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{) }\OperatorTok{&}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{(mtcars}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{wt }\OperatorTok{<}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{)  }\CommentTok{# select only columns with 4 cylinders and a weight under 2 tons}
\NormalTok{mtcars[index,]}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
                mpg cyl disp  hp drat    wt  qsec vs am gear carb
Honda Civic    30.4   4 75.7  52 4.93 1.615 18.52  1  1    4    2
Toyota Corolla 33.9   4 71.1  65 4.22 1.835 19.90  1  1    4    1
Fiat X1-9      27.3   4 79.0  66 4.08 1.935 18.90  1  1    4    1
Lotus Europa   30.4   4 95.1 113 3.77 1.513 16.90  1  1    5    2
                          car
Honda Civic       Honda Civic
Toyota Corolla Toyota Corolla
Fiat X1-9           Fiat X1-9
Lotus Europa     Lotus Europa
\end{verbatim}

In \texttt{dplyr}, the same thing can be accomplished with the \texttt{filter} function:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{filter}\NormalTok{(mtcars, cyl}\OperatorTok{==}\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{, wt}\OperatorTok{<}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{)  }\CommentTok{# select only columns with 4 cylinders and a weight under 2 tons}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
                mpg cyl disp  hp drat    wt  qsec vs am gear carb
Honda Civic    30.4   4 75.7  52 4.93 1.615 18.52  1  1    4    2
Toyota Corolla 33.9   4 71.1  65 4.22 1.835 19.90  1  1    4    1
Fiat X1-9      27.3   4 79.0  66 4.08 1.935 18.90  1  1    4    1
Lotus Europa   30.4   4 95.1 113 3.77 1.513 16.90  1  1    5    2
                          car
Honda Civic       Honda Civic
Toyota Corolla Toyota Corolla
Fiat X1-9           Fiat X1-9
Lotus Europa     Lotus Europa
\end{verbatim}

This might already seem like an improvement, because it requires less code, but most people use the filter function \emph{differently} than this.
\texttt{dplyr} uses a \emph{pipe} (which looks like this \texttt{\%\textgreater{}\%}) to structure arguments differently.
Here's how the same function looks with the pipe:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# do the same filtering, but use the pipe, %>%}
\NormalTok{mtcars }\OperatorTok{%>%}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{filter}\NormalTok{(cyl }\OperatorTok{==}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{, wt }\OperatorTok{<}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{)  }
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
                mpg cyl disp  hp drat    wt  qsec vs am gear carb
Honda Civic    30.4   4 75.7  52 4.93 1.615 18.52  1  1    4    2
Toyota Corolla 33.9   4 71.1  65 4.22 1.835 19.90  1  1    4    1
Fiat X1-9      27.3   4 79.0  66 4.08 1.935 18.90  1  1    4    1
Lotus Europa   30.4   4 95.1 113 3.77 1.513 16.90  1  1    5    2
                          car
Honda Civic       Honda Civic
Toyota Corolla Toyota Corolla
Fiat X1-9           Fiat X1-9
Lotus Europa     Lotus Europa
\end{verbatim}

Basically, the pipe operator says ``Take the think on the left and use it as the first argument for the function on the right''.
This may seem backwards at first, but it allows the chaining of multiple functions together in an order that reflects the order of computation that R will use (more on this after the next example).
Recall that here's how we select a column in base R:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{mtcars[,}\StringTok{"qsec"}\NormalTok{] }\CommentTok{# select the qsec column}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
 [1] 16.46 17.02 18.61 19.44 17.02 20.22 15.84 20.00 22.90 18.30 18.90 17.40
[13] 17.60 18.00 17.98 17.82 17.42 19.47 18.52 19.90 20.01 16.87 17.30 15.41
[25] 17.05 18.90 16.70 16.90 14.50 15.50 14.60 18.60
\end{verbatim}

And here's how to do the same thing in \texttt{dplyr}:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{mtcars }\OperatorTok{%>%}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{select}\NormalTok{(qsec)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
                     qsec
Mazda RX4           16.46
Mazda RX4 Wag       17.02
Datsun 710          18.61
Hornet 4 Drive      19.44
Hornet Sportabout   17.02
Valiant             20.22
Duster 360          15.84
Merc 240D           20.00
Merc 230            22.90
Merc 280            18.30
Merc 280C           18.90
Merc 450SE          17.40
Merc 450SL          17.60
Merc 450SLC         18.00
Cadillac Fleetwood  17.98
Lincoln Continental 17.82
Chrysler Imperial   17.42
Fiat 128            19.47
Honda Civic         18.52
Toyota Corolla      19.90
Toyota Corona       20.01
Dodge Challenger    16.87
AMC Javelin         17.30
Camaro Z28          15.41
Pontiac Firebird    17.05
Fiat X1-9           18.90
Porsche 914-2       16.70
Lotus Europa        16.90
Ford Pantera L      14.50
Ferrari Dino        15.50
Maserati Bora       14.60
Volvo 142E          18.60
\end{verbatim}

Notice that \texttt{dplyr} has maintained the data frame structure, while indexing has not.
We \emph{can} get the same thing from indexing if we use the \texttt{drop=F} argument:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{mtcars[,}\StringTok{"qsec"}\NormalTok{, drop=F]}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
                     qsec
Mazda RX4           16.46
Mazda RX4 Wag       17.02
Datsun 710          18.61
Hornet 4 Drive      19.44
Hornet Sportabout   17.02
Valiant             20.22
Duster 360          15.84
Merc 240D           20.00
Merc 230            22.90
Merc 280            18.30
Merc 280C           18.90
Merc 450SE          17.40
Merc 450SL          17.60
Merc 450SLC         18.00
Cadillac Fleetwood  17.98
Lincoln Continental 17.82
Chrysler Imperial   17.42
Fiat 128            19.47
Honda Civic         18.52
Toyota Corolla      19.90
Toyota Corona       20.01
Dodge Challenger    16.87
AMC Javelin         17.30
Camaro Z28          15.41
Pontiac Firebird    17.05
Fiat X1-9           18.90
Porsche 914-2       16.70
Lotus Europa        16.90
Ford Pantera L      14.50
Ferrari Dino        15.50
Maserati Bora       14.60
Volvo 142E          18.60
\end{verbatim}

The pipe works with the \texttt{select} function because the first argument of \texttt{select} is the data frame to select from, so the pipe says ``Use \texttt{mtcars} as the first argument of the \texttt{select} function''.
Here's how we would do the filtering and selection at the same time in \texttt{dplyr}:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{mtcars }\OperatorTok{%>%}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{filter}\NormalTok{(cyl }\OperatorTok{==}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{, wt }\OperatorTok{<}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{) }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{select}\NormalTok{(qsec)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
                qsec
Honda Civic    18.52
Toyota Corolla 19.90
Fiat X1-9      18.90
Lotus Europa   16.90
\end{verbatim}

Since the result of the filter function is a data frame (which is why it printed in the result in the example above!), that data frame can be piped into the \texttt{select} function.
This easy chaining of arguments is one reason why people love to work with tidyverse packages.

\begin{bonus}
The pipe operator is one of the most common elements of the tidyverse
group of packages. One of the tidyverse packages called
\href{https://github.com/tidyverse/magrittr/blob/master/README.md}{magrittr}
even uses the pipe operator as its official logo, with the slogan ``Ceci
n'est pas un pipe'', a reference to this
\href{https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Treachery_of_Images}{famous work
of art}.
\end{bonus}

\texttt{dplyr} can also summarize columns in different groups similarly to the \texttt{tapply} function.
Here's an example of \texttt{tapply}:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# find the mean mpg for different numbers of cylinders:}
\KeywordTok{tapply}\NormalTok{(mtcars}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{mpg, mtcars}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{cyl, mean)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
       4        6        8 
26.66364 19.74286 15.10000 
\end{verbatim}

In \texttt{dplyr} this is accomplished with the \texttt{group\_by} and \texttt{summarize} functions:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{mtcars }\OperatorTok{%>%}\StringTok{ }
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{group_by}\NormalTok{(cyl) }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{summarize}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{ave_mpg =} \KeywordTok{mean}\NormalTok{(mpg))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
`summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
\end{verbatim}

\begin{verbatim}
# A tibble: 3 x 2
    cyl ave_mpg
  <dbl>   <dbl>
1     4    26.7
2     6    19.7
3     8    15.1
\end{verbatim}

With only a few functions, we can now start to chain together quite complex operations in a human readable way:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{mtcars }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{filter}\NormalTok{(wt }\OperatorTok{>}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{) }\OperatorTok{%>%}\StringTok{       }\CommentTok{# filter out cars below 2 tons}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{group_by}\NormalTok{(cyl, gear) }\OperatorTok{%>%}\StringTok{  }\CommentTok{# group by number of cylinders and number of gears}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{summarize}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{n =} \KeywordTok{n}\NormalTok{(),              }\CommentTok{# compute number of cars in each group}
            \DataTypeTok{ave_mpg =} \KeywordTok{mean}\NormalTok{(mpg),  }\CommentTok{# compute average mpg}
            \DataTypeTok{sd_mpg =} \KeywordTok{sd}\NormalTok{(mpg))     }\CommentTok{# compute standard deviation of mpg}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
`summarise()` regrouping output by 'cyl' (override with `.groups` argument)
\end{verbatim}

\begin{verbatim}
# A tibble: 8 x 5
# Groups:   cyl [3]
    cyl  gear     n ave_mpg sd_mpg
  <dbl> <dbl> <int>   <dbl>  <dbl>
1     4     3     1    21.5 NA    
2     4     4     5    24.8  4.40 
3     4     5     1    26   NA    
4     6     3     2    19.8  2.33 
5     6     4     4    19.8  1.55 
6     6     5     1    19.7 NA    
7     8     3    12    15.0  2.77 
8     8     5     2    15.4  0.566
\end{verbatim}

Again, this is only a \emph{teaser} of the capabilities of \texttt{dplyr}, but the hope is that if/when you encounter \texttt{dplyr} in the future, you will at least have an introduction to some of the basic concepts.

\hypertarget{working-with-character-strings-with-stringr}{%
\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Working With Character Strings with \emph{stringr}}{Working With Character Strings with stringr}}\label{working-with-character-strings-with-stringr}}

\emph{stringr} is another tidyverse package that provides functions for easily working with character strings.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# install.packages("stringr")  # install if you haven't before }
\KeywordTok{library}\NormalTok{(stringr)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

To show some of the capabilities of the \texttt{stringr} package, we'll read in ``Pride and Prejudice'' which is available on Project Gutenberg \href{http://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/1342}{here}.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{lines <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{readLines}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{file}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"data_raw/pride_and_prejudice.txt"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"rt"}\NormalTok{))}
\KeywordTok{length}\NormalTok{(lines)  }\CommentTok{# the book is now a long character vector}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] 14594
\end{verbatim}

The first thing we'll do is convert the text into ``UTF-8'' formatting using \texttt{stringr}'s \texttt{str\_conv} function:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{lines <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{str_conv}\NormalTok{(lines, }\StringTok{"UTF-8"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Right now, each element of \texttt{lines} is just a single line from the original text file.
Let's collapse all the elements into a single character string:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{book <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{str_c}\NormalTok{(lines, }\DataTypeTok{collapse=}\StringTok{" "}\NormalTok{)}
\KeywordTok{nchar}\NormalTok{(book)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] 775739
\end{verbatim}

Now we can split the book in a more sensible way.
Let's split the string at the end of each sentence using the \texttt{strsplit} function (this is a base R function, actually).

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{sent <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{strsplit}\NormalTok{(book, }\StringTok{"(?<=[[:punct:]])}\CharTok{\textbackslash{}\textbackslash{}}\StringTok{s(?=[A-Z])"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{perl=}\NormalTok{T)  }\CommentTok{# split by end of sentences}
\NormalTok{sent <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{unlist}\NormalTok{(sent)  }\CommentTok{# convert list to character vector}
\KeywordTok{length}\NormalTok{(sent)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] 5175
\end{verbatim}

\begin{bonus}
The \texttt{strsplit} function above used something called a
\emph{regular expression} to identify patterns that indicate the end of
a sentence. Regular expressions are commonly used in programming, and
can be confusing when first encountered. This is okay! You might want to
take a look at
\href{https://paulvanderlaken.com/2017/10/03/regular-expressions-in-r-part-1-introduction-and-base-r-functions/}{this
resource} if you want more info on regular expressions in R.
\end{bonus}

The \texttt{sent} vector now contains sentences as elements.
Let's look at an arbitrary sentence:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{sent[}\DecValTok{300}\NormalTok{]}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] "I should think she had       as good a chance of happiness as if she were to be studying his       character for a twelvemonth."
\end{verbatim}

We notice that there are some extra spaces in the sentence, which probably result from the formatting of the original text file.
Ignoring that for now, we can find all sentences containing the word ``Jane'':

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{has_jane <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{str_detect}\NormalTok{(sent, }\StringTok{"Jane"}\NormalTok{) }\CommentTok{# returns logical vector }
\KeywordTok{sum}\NormalTok{(has_jane)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] 265
\end{verbatim}

We see there are 265 sentences with the string ``Jane'' in them. Let's look at some of them:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{jane_sent <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{sent[has_jane]}
\NormalTok{jane_sent[}\DecValTok{100}\OperatorTok{:}\DecValTok{105}\NormalTok{]}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] "She could think of nothing       else; and yet whether Bingleys regard had really died away, or       were suppressed by his friends interference; whether he had been       aware of Janes attachment, or whether it had escaped his       observation; whatever were the case, though her opinion of him       must be materially affected by the difference, her sisters       situation remained the same, her peace equally wounded.        A day or two passed before Jane had courage to speak of her       feelings to Elizabeth; but at last, on Mrs."
[2] "It cannot last long.       He will be forgot, and we shall all be as we were before.        Elizabeth looked at her sister with incredulous solicitude, but       said nothing.        You doubt me, cried Jane, slightly colouring; indeed, you have       no reason."                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        
[3] "A little time, thereforeI shall certainly try to       get the better.        With a stronger voice she soon added, I have this comfort       immediately, that it has not been more than an error of fancy on       my side, and that it has done no harm to anyone but myself.        My dear Jane! exclaimed Elizabeth, you are too good."                                                                                                                                                                                                               
[4] "My       dear Jane,"                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               
[5] "You shall not, for the sake of one individual, change the       meaning of principle and integrity, nor endeavour to persuade       yourself or me, that selfishness is prudence, and insensibility       of danger security for happiness.        I must think your language too strong in speaking of both,       replied Jane; and I hope you will be convinced of it by seeing       them happy together."                                                                                                                                                 
[6] "They may wish many things besides       his happiness; they may wish his increase of wealth and       consequence; they may wish him to marry a girl who has all the       importance of money, great connections, and pride.        Beyond a doubt, they do wish him to choose Miss Darcy, replied       Jane; but this may be from better feelings than you are       supposing."                                                                                                                                                                            
\end{verbatim}

We can also count the number of occurrences of a string in the book using the \texttt{str\_count} function:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{str_count}\NormalTok{(book, }\StringTok{"pride"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] 46
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{str_count}\NormalTok{(book, }\StringTok{"prejudice"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] 8
\end{verbatim}

To see more capability of the \texttt{stringr} package, you can check out this \href{http://edrub.in/CheatSheets/cheatSheetStringr.pdf}{cheat sheet}.
